WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.520
Because across the board, we realized that bi-specifics are very disparate across myeloma.

00:00:09.980 --> 00:00:14.580
We are very spoiled academic sites, but community sites really need to get access to these.

00:00:15.100 --> 00:00:16.740
And I think it's our job to partner with them.

00:00:18.560 --> 00:00:23.520
So here's a couple examples to kind of show partnerships throughout history here.

00:00:23.620 --> 00:00:25.160
So we have Jack and Colby.

00:00:25.620 --> 00:00:26.700
I know this is controversial.

00:00:26.700 --> 00:00:30.540
My husband said I should have put a Bulls team together from the 90s.

00:00:32.460 --> 00:00:40.840
We have, you know, for those of us that are millennials, we really gravitate to, I think, Rachel and Monica.

00:00:42.220 --> 00:00:50.840
And then I got to say, yeah, for the boomers, but also for myself, I am a huge Al Pacino fan.

00:00:51.580 --> 00:00:55.940
So you have Robert De Niro and Al Pacino, who are actually real life friends.

00:00:56.700 --> 00:01:06.400
Okay, so just going through, the point of this slide is to show all the different nuances between the four FDA-approved myeloma bi-specifics

00:01:06.400 --> 00:01:12.260
and how there's all these different nuances between step-up dosing, the frequency of the dosing,

00:01:12.620 --> 00:01:17.780
and even with intelcodamab, it originally came out with two different dose strategies for ramp-up.

00:01:18.260 --> 00:01:21.080
And that ramp-up then went to every week or every two weeks.

00:01:23.220 --> 00:01:26.240
So there's a lot of challenges within step-up dosing.

00:01:26.700 --> 00:01:34.020
Just within the academic center and then trying to figure out, well, how are we going to now navigate our community practice positions

00:01:34.020 --> 00:01:40.000
to learn how to do this along with every other thing that they're expected to navigate?

00:01:40.700 --> 00:01:43.280
So we're focused on myeloma.

00:01:43.920 --> 00:01:49.840
And I think it's our job to really figure out a blueprint within the resources that exist in the community

00:01:49.840 --> 00:01:54.060
that it can easily transition from us as the expert to them.

00:01:54.420 --> 00:01:56.540
So I'll go through kind of a plan A versus a plan B.

00:01:56.540 --> 00:01:56.660
Okay.

00:01:56.700 --> 00:02:01.280
So the limitation of community practice is probably the number one issue.

00:02:01.500 --> 00:02:03.820
Like it was mentioned previously from some of my colleagues here,

00:02:03.920 --> 00:02:06.720
a lot of them don't even have access to a hospital to admit patients to.

00:02:07.240 --> 00:02:10.240
There's also a lot of fear of CRS and ICANNs.

00:02:10.600 --> 00:02:13.780
The REMS program itself brings a lot of that on.

00:02:14.340 --> 00:02:16.540
And I think one of our jobs is education.

00:02:17.660 --> 00:02:23.820
The travel distance to get to us, it's going to be far easier for patients to be able to get this in their own backyard.

00:02:24.800 --> 00:02:26.540
Caregiver support, that's going to remain a barrier.

00:02:26.540 --> 00:02:28.960
It's going to be a big issue regardless of where patients are getting this.

00:02:30.020 --> 00:02:33.020
Education of the patients, the clinical team.

00:02:33.160 --> 00:02:37.780
So I do a lot of going into our regional community practice sites.

00:02:38.340 --> 00:02:43.680
And there's a lot of people that need to be involved in the clinical team education.

00:02:44.360 --> 00:02:47.840
After our support is going to be a huge issue too in the community.

00:02:48.100 --> 00:02:52.280
So not all of us have access to a third-party monitoring system.

00:02:52.420 --> 00:02:56.180
So when we developed our outpatient program, we actually opted to not use one.

00:02:56.380 --> 00:03:04.500
We did that on purpose because we want to think about next steps of how are we going to transition this from our center to any center.

00:03:07.020 --> 00:03:10.320
So we have to work with our pharmaceutical colleagues.

00:03:10.760 --> 00:03:13.540
That would be those in the back of the room here.

00:03:13.980 --> 00:03:15.920
Consortiums, working groups.

00:03:15.920 --> 00:03:26.120
We have to develop and publish real-world data on how to manage this from step-up or the plan B, which would be taking patients,

00:03:26.220 --> 00:03:29.840
we do the step-up at the academic site, and then they return home.

00:03:30.600 --> 00:03:31.620
I think plan A is better.

00:03:31.940 --> 00:03:33.320
We'll go over plan A and B next.

00:03:33.960 --> 00:03:39.140
We need to really partner and be more accessible to our community partners.

00:03:39.860 --> 00:03:46.840
By partnering with them, it doesn't mean that they're going to sit there and call you at 2 in the morning and use you as the after-hours service.

00:03:47.240 --> 00:03:48.160
That's not the point.

00:03:48.580 --> 00:03:53.820
The point is to make yourself available for a text message here or there and be able to help guide them.

00:03:53.820 --> 00:03:55.220
Once they get through the first couple,

00:03:56.060 --> 00:04:01.680
I'm very surprised at how well they've adapted to becoming comfortable doing this.

00:04:03.140 --> 00:04:11.600
So plan A is going to be doing this whole thing outpatient and being able to have the community docs work within their resources.

00:04:12.480 --> 00:04:19.020
So the prior presentations here talking about using dexamethasone or using tocilizumab.

00:04:19.020 --> 00:04:22.820
So when you look at dexamethasone, you'll get what's been published out there.

00:04:23.320 --> 00:04:25.900
Those rates basically cut the CRS rate.

00:04:25.900 --> 00:04:32.940
When you look at tocilizumab, though, it's driving most of the rates below 10%.

00:04:32.940 --> 00:04:37.840
And what we are seeing is almost entirely grade one that can be safely managed all outpatient.

00:04:38.260 --> 00:04:40.400
So I really think it should be kind of the best of both worlds.

00:04:40.920 --> 00:04:43.760
I do think the prophylactic TOSI is probably the best option.

00:04:44.340 --> 00:04:47.340
Having it on NCCN should not be a huge barrier.

00:04:47.600 --> 00:04:53.780
As far as people mentioning the cost of acquisition of the product, there's a lot of biosimilars that are coming.

00:04:53.780 --> 00:04:54.980
There's a lot more competition.

00:04:55.740 --> 00:04:58.400
There's allowing price reductions in tocilizumab.

00:04:59.060 --> 00:05:03.180
It should not be an insurance reimbursement issue, which I think is what we were originally worried about.

00:05:04.140 --> 00:05:10.000
Being able to have what we call pocket docs so that the patients are instructed on what to do if they were to get a low-grade fever.

00:05:13.360 --> 00:05:18.020
So there's a lot of pros to doing a plan A of having the whole thing outpatient.

00:05:18.120 --> 00:05:20.180
The patients are able to remain close to home.

00:05:20.360 --> 00:05:25.580
We're able to start having a plan in place to work within any community.

00:05:25.580 --> 00:05:35.440
We're able to have a community practice to use the resources that they have and be able to not rely on the use of a hospital system.

00:05:35.440 --> 00:05:42.880
So not needing the use of emergency rooms except in very rare events, not needing to have hospitalized patients.

00:05:43.400 --> 00:05:55.420
I think that that is our main goal is be able to get this to a point where we're really having pretty close to zero reason to be using emergency rooms and hospitals with this step-up.

00:05:55.420 --> 00:06:25.260
I think that that is our main goal is be able to get this to a point where we're really having pretty close to zero reason to be using emergency rooms and hospitals with this step-up.

00:06:25.260 --> 00:06:34.080
The people that are looking at all the behind-the-scenes and thinking of these rare one-in-a-million scenarios, and that's the big stopgap.

00:06:34.860 --> 00:06:38.740
Reliance on an emergency room and the rare refractory CRS or ICAMs.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:40.880
Now, plan B.

00:06:41.420 --> 00:06:44.260
This is what a lot of us actually started doing in the real world is plan B.

00:06:45.040 --> 00:06:46.760
They partner with us.

00:06:47.160 --> 00:06:48.760
We bring them to us.

00:06:48.960 --> 00:06:50.240
We step them up.

00:06:50.240 --> 00:06:53.120
We get them through the acute tox phase.

00:06:53.780 --> 00:06:55.240
And then, ideally, they react.

00:06:55.260 --> 00:06:55.920
We return home.

00:06:56.480 --> 00:07:01.240
How often this actually happens in the real world, not as often as we'd like it to happen.

00:07:02.100 --> 00:07:08.680
So, the REMS program, I think, has been very misleading with about the timing and severity of CRS and ICAMs.

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:18.720
When you get in there and you do your training for REMS and you're having a new center look at all this, that is where the administrative leads get concerned.

00:07:19.040 --> 00:07:25.240
They start to see all this, well, if we see a grade three, you're recommending considering placing them in an ICU.

00:07:25.260 --> 00:07:30.000
We don't even have hospital admission privileges.

00:07:30.400 --> 00:07:33.820
So, how are we going to mitigate this and deal with all these safety issues?

00:07:35.440 --> 00:07:40.100
So, the pros of this, it does work within most existing infrastructure resources.

00:07:40.800 --> 00:07:44.340
You send your patient up two, three hours away.

00:07:44.740 --> 00:07:46.040
They do the step-up dosing.

00:07:46.480 --> 00:07:51.640
The cons, there's a lot of fear amongst the community practitioners that they're never going to see their patient again.

00:07:52.020 --> 00:07:53.020
Their patient's going to go.

00:07:53.400 --> 00:07:54.540
They're never going to come home.

00:07:54.540 --> 00:07:54.680
They're never going to come home.

00:07:54.680 --> 00:07:54.720
They're never going to come home.

00:07:54.720 --> 00:07:54.840
They're never going to come home.

00:07:55.260 --> 00:07:56.660
Does that happen in reality?

00:07:57.200 --> 00:07:58.840
In some circumstances, yes.

00:07:58.960 --> 00:08:03.340
But I think as an academic physician, we want our patients to return home.

00:08:03.680 --> 00:08:06.440
We want them to be able to be with their referring doctor.

00:08:07.020 --> 00:08:09.920
I think we're reinforcing this fear about CRS and ICAMs.

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:11.640
I think it's being overblown quite a bit.

00:08:12.180 --> 00:08:15.360
And so, this plan of hybrid model is kind of reinforcing that.

00:08:15.420 --> 00:08:17.600
I don't think we're going to get beyond and get to plan A.

00:08:18.260 --> 00:08:22.320
And then you need to have this really good communication for smooth transitions between sites.

00:08:24.720 --> 00:08:25.000
Thank you.

00:08:25.260 --> 00:08:26.060
All right.
